Einstein didn't have a
limitation with electricity.

00:09:40.460 --> 00:09:43.280
They often say you
can do mathematics

00:09:43.280 --> 00:09:46.330
and theoretical physics
with just the pencil, paper,

00:09:46.330 --> 00:09:48.232
and a dust bin.

00:09:48.232 --> 00:09:50.309
A waste basket.

00:09:50.309 --> 00:09:51.850
Cynics will say you
can do philosophy

00:09:51.850 --> 00:09:53.790
in exactly the same
way, but you don't need

00:09:53.790 --> 00:09:55.710
the dustbin, which is kind of

00:09:55.710 --> 00:09:56.360
Cruel.

00:09:56.360 --> 00:09:58.820
Einstein himself loved
good philosophers.

00:09:58.820 --> 00:10:01.830
Kant, at one point, had an image
of space-time diagrams, which

00:10:01.830 --> 00:10:03.760
is really good in the 1770s.

00:10:03.760 --> 00:10:06.190
Hume's notions about
causality and just looking

00:10:06.190 --> 00:10:08.400
at what you observe where
than trying to understand

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:09.370
what's going on inside.

00:10:09.370 --> 00:10:11.090
These are great
powerful notions.

00:10:11.090 --> 00:10:13.450
So Einstein, the
equivalent of the 6:00 PM

00:10:13.450 --> 00:10:17.430
stop-- he had terrible
problems in relationships.

00:10:17.430 --> 00:10:20.070
After his best friend died
when they were both old men,

00:10:20.070 --> 00:10:22.420
Einstein wrote the best
friend's family, Michele Besso

00:10:22.420 --> 00:10:24.152
and said, I admired
your dad for me

00:10:24.152 --> 00:10:25.860
a nice guy and a
sounding board, but what

00:10:25.860 --> 00:10:28.940
I admired best was that he made
a relationship with one woman

00:10:28.940 --> 00:10:32.040
work for his entire life,
something which I, sadly,

00:10:32.040 --> 00:10:33.350
have failed in twice.

00:10:33.350 --> 00:10:35.620
So Einstein had
spent a lot of time

00:10:35.620 --> 00:10:38.160
moving from apartment to
apartment, flats to flat,

00:10:38.160 --> 00:10:39.940
escaping from one
person, having an affair

00:10:39.940 --> 00:10:41.970
with the wrong person,
going off to another one.

00:10:41.970 --> 00:10:44.010
It really restricted his time.

00:10:44.010 --> 00:10:46.059
Sometimes he was
writing in trains

00:10:46.059 --> 00:10:47.600
because he couldn't
stay in any city.

00:10:47.600 --> 00:10:50.500
So he had constraints
on his time.

00:10:50.500 --> 00:10:52.960
For his tools, developing
your own tools,

00:10:52.960 --> 00:10:55.280
he developed what's
now kind of standard.

00:10:55.280 --> 00:10:57.440
He really developed tensors.

00:10:57.440 --> 00:11:00.360
Those of you who aren't with a
technical background, scalars

00:11:00.360 --> 00:11:02.800
are numbers and
stuff, and vectors

00:11:02.800 --> 00:11:05.430
are a number with a
direction like an arrow,

00:11:05.430 --> 00:11:08.630
and tensors just generalize
that a little bit more.

00:11:08.630 --> 00:11:10.847
It's in the appendix
to the book.

00:11:10.847 --> 00:11:12.430
So he developed that,
and he specially

00:11:12.430 --> 00:11:14.300
developed interesting
ways of understanding

00:11:14.300 --> 00:11:15.250
surfaces and stuff.

00:11:15.250 --> 00:11:18.500
It was his own fresh tools,
which meant nobody else had it.

00:11:18.500 --> 00:11:21.000
Imagine if you have a tool
which nobody else has.

00:11:21.000 --> 00:11:23.510
There was an athlete
40, 50 years ago

00:11:23.510 --> 00:11:24.830
who was a mid-level jumper.

00:11:24.830 --> 00:11:29.130
He wasn't incredible, but he had
found a way-- I think was Dick.

00:11:29.130 --> 00:11:31.637
Fosbury was his last name--
of jumping backwards.

00:11:31.637 --> 00:11:33.720
This is the famous way
that high jumpers jump now.

00:11:33.720 --> 00:11:35.580
When he had that
tool nobody else did,

00:11:35.580 --> 00:11:37.890
he was great, even though he
wasn't a stunning athlete.

00:11:37.890 --> 00:11:39.890
Once everybody else had
it, he had to fade away.

00:11:39.890 --> 00:11:40.890
He wasn't that good.

00:11:40.890 --> 00:11:42.137
Advantages to being first.

00:11:42.137 --> 00:11:43.970
And then the other great
thing that Einstein

00:11:43.970 --> 00:11:45.752
was good at his
mid-level abstraction.

00:11:45.752 --> 00:11:46.710
That's a bit technical.

00:11:46.710 --> 00:11:48.040
I get into it in the book.

00:11:48.040 --> 00:11:51.560
It was a way how you
can view any physics

00:11:51.560 --> 00:11:54.360
problem independent of
whoever's watching, whether I'm

00:11:54.360 --> 00:11:58.380
jumping up and down, whether
I'm moving quickly or slowly.

00:11:58.380 --> 00:12:00.440
How would things
seem if everybody

00:12:00.440 --> 00:12:02.970
is able to view things,
and you can't tell

00:12:02.970 --> 00:12:05.170
who has a special position.

00:12:05.170 --> 00:12:07.080
It's kind of very
much a democracy.

00:12:07.080 --> 00:12:09.130
I know it's kind of waffly
to say it like that,

00:12:09.130 --> 00:12:11.010
so I have to go and leave
the details in the book.

00:12:11.010 --> 00:12:13.265
But he had his unique tools,
he had pressures on time,

00:12:13.265 --> 00:12:15.929
and he had a beautiful
mid-level abstraction.

00:12:15.929 --> 00:12:18.220
He wasn't trying to solve a
particular physical problem

00:12:18.220 --> 00:12:20.660
down here, nor was he saying
I'm going to be the best.

00:12:20.660 --> 00:12:21.620
I'm going to achieve.

00:12:21.620 --> 00:12:23.490
I'm going to create greatness.

00:12:23.490 --> 00:12:27.054
And his abstractions were
very, very, very good.

00:12:27.054 --> 00:12:28.470
Anyways, it turns
out at one point

00:12:28.470 --> 00:12:30.120
he drew the mechanism
of how creativity

00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:32.050
happens inside his own brain.

00:12:32.050 --> 00:12:34.290
And those of you who read
German as well as I do,

00:12:34.290 --> 00:12:37.330
which is not too well, will
not be following the German.

00:12:37.330 --> 00:12:39.940
What I'm going to do
while this slide's up,

00:12:39.940 --> 00:12:43.850
I'm going to draw something
like that roughly on the board.

00:12:43.850 --> 00:12:46.980
So what Einstein said is down
here, things in the real world

00:12:46.980 --> 00:12:48.470
events and stuff
that you look at,

00:12:48.470 --> 00:12:50.450
and then we make
a creative jump,

00:12:50.450 --> 00:12:53.280
a creative leap of the
imagination going up here.

00:12:53.280 --> 00:12:55.920
And from this vantage
point, we see fresh things.

00:12:55.920 --> 00:12:56.820
We're up here.

00:12:56.820 --> 00:12:58.560
Remember, and this
is a mid-level thing.

00:12:58.560 --> 00:12:59.607
It's not incredibly high.

00:12:59.607 --> 00:13:01.690
It isn't I'm going to
survey the world like a god,

00:13:01.690 --> 00:13:03.560
but it's not a detail
thing down here.

00:13:03.560 --> 00:13:06.570
And from here, you
draw conclusions.

00:13:06.570 --> 00:13:08.740
And if the
conclusions are right,

00:13:08.740 --> 00:13:10.280
they match what's down there.

00:13:10.280 --> 00:13:12.690
And then this jump up
has been correct, right?

00:13:12.690 --> 00:13:14.315
Very simple form.

00:13:14.315 --> 00:13:16.100
That was the sort of form.

00:13:16.100 --> 00:13:18.560
And that's what he
said, how it works.

00:13:18.560 --> 00:13:20.420
And from that perch,
you can see everything.

00:13:20.420 --> 00:13:22.750
Anyways, it's a great idea,
and Einstein followed it

00:13:22.750 --> 00:13:24.620
successfully for
quite a few years.

00:13:24.620 --> 00:13:28.220
But then after about 20 years--
this happened so often--

00:13:28.220 --> 00:13:30.160
he stopped following it.

00:13:30.160 --> 00:13:32.620
I have time to tell you a little
bit of the story about how

00:13:32.620 --> 00:13:33.620
he stopped following it.

00:13:33.620 --> 00:13:36.100
The book is mostly about that.

00:13:36.100 --> 00:13:41.040
It turns out in 1915, 1916,
100 years ago in the middle

00:13:41.040 --> 00:13:44.030
of wartime Berlin he came
up with an equation that

00:13:44.030 --> 00:13:47.922
describes the entire
shape of the universe.

00:13:47.922 --> 00:13:49.630
As a rough example--
and again, apologies

00:13:49.630 --> 00:13:52.200
to people who've done physics
at a high level-- as a very

00:13:52.200 --> 00:13:54.300
rough image, imagine
that space is

00:13:54.300 --> 00:13:56.720
like a flat trampoline
or a rubber sheet,

00:13:56.720 --> 00:13:59.520
and if I take a little
ball bearing and flick it,

00:13:59.520 --> 00:14:00.830
it will go in a straight line.

00:14:00.830 --> 00:14:01.960
And if I flick in
some other way,

00:14:01.960 --> 00:14:02.970
it will go in a straight line.

00:14:02.970 --> 00:14:04.553
Those might be
something like planets.

00:14:04.553 --> 00:14:05.650
You just flick him along.

00:14:05.650 --> 00:14:08.000
You see the big
finger coming down

00:14:08.000 --> 00:14:09.390
from south of King's Cross.

00:14:09.390 --> 00:14:10.360
OK.

00:14:10.360 --> 00:14:14.010
If you take a rock or a heavier
ball and put it in the middle

00:14:14.010 --> 00:14:15.950
that sheet, it'll sag
down in that sheet.

00:14:15.950 --> 00:14:18.150
And think of that as
the sun or something.

00:14:18.150 --> 00:14:20.672
Then if I flick a ball
bearing, the ball bearing,

00:14:20.672 --> 00:14:22.130
instead of going
straight-- it will

00:14:22.130 --> 00:14:24.330
if it's far away-- if the
sheet's sagging down here,

00:14:24.330 --> 00:14:26.520
the ball bearing
will veer around it

00:14:26.520 --> 00:14:28.357
like in a billiards or
pool table and stuff.

00:14:28.357 --> 00:14:29.190
Kind of makes sense.

00:14:29.190 --> 00:14:30.550
Again, it's only a metaphor.

00:14:30.550 --> 00:14:31.720
Here it's curving in space.

00:14:31.720 --> 00:14:34.350
In fact, in reality it's
curving in space-time

00:14:34.350 --> 00:14:35.780
it's a wonderful notion.

00:14:35.780 --> 00:14:39.420
Force then becomes just
a distortion of space.

00:14:39.420 --> 00:14:41.050
Geometry leads you along.

00:14:41.050 --> 00:14:43.859
An example there is two people
walking to the North Pole.

00:14:43.859 --> 00:14:45.900
You can start in different
points on the equator,

00:14:45.900 --> 00:14:47.760
and you look at each other--
you're a few yards apart--

00:14:47.760 --> 00:14:49.210
and you say, we're
going to stay parallel.

00:14:49.210 --> 00:14:50.584
We're each going
to go due north.

00:14:50.584 --> 00:14:52.860
But you realize that geometry
will force you together.

00:14:52.860 --> 00:14:54.860
You'll see this person
coming closer and closer.

00:14:54.860 --> 00:14:56.300
You'll say, you're
not going straight.

00:14:56.300 --> 00:14:57.341
He'll say, the heck I am.

00:14:57.341 --> 00:14:58.660
I'm going perfectly straight.

00:14:58.660 --> 00:15:02.050
So what appears to be a force
come from the distortions

00:15:02.050 --> 00:15:02.614
of geometry.

00:15:02.614 --> 00:15:05.280
That's a two-dimensional surface
in our three-dimensional space.

00:15:05.280 --> 00:15:09.410
Space-time is four-dimensional
so that's how it works.

00:15:09.410 --> 00:15:11.760
Anyways, the details
are in the book.

00:15:11.760 --> 00:15:12.760
That isn't what matters.

00:15:12.760 --> 00:15:14.134
What matters is
Einstein came out

00:15:14.134 --> 00:15:18.210
of it with a beautiful
equation g equals t.

00:15:18.210 --> 00:15:21.260
Geometry creates
how things move,

00:15:21.260 --> 00:15:23.850
and the structure
and shape of things,

00:15:23.850 --> 00:15:26.500
which includes mass and
energy, will shape the geometry

00:15:26.500 --> 00:15:27.170
around it.

00:15:27.170 --> 00:15:29.410
The fact of a heavy
bowling ball will

00:15:29.410 --> 00:15:31.570
sag the sheet of
space-time around it,

00:15:31.570 --> 00:15:34.287
and the curvature of space-time
will show that there's

00:15:34.287 --> 00:15:35.370
got to be something there.

00:15:35.370 --> 00:15:36.870
You know, something
there behind it.

00:15:36.870 --> 00:15:38.004
What a beautiful idea.

00:15:38.004 --> 00:15:40.420
Among other things Einstein
worked out shortly afterwards,

00:15:40.420 --> 00:15:43.300
in 1917, was that this
predicted that the universe was

00:15:43.300 --> 00:15:44.170
expanding.

00:15:44.170 --> 00:15:45.850
What an amazing idea.

00:15:45.850 --> 00:15:47.970
And he went to his astronomer
of friends and said,

00:15:47.970 --> 00:15:49.450
I've predicted the
universe is expanding.

00:15:49.450 --> 00:15:50.950
These two simple
equations that seem

00:15:50.950 --> 00:15:52.750
to reveal the truth
of the universe

00:15:52.750 --> 00:15:54.470
explain the universe
is expanding.

00:15:54.470 --> 00:15:58.154
And his astronomer friends,
in 1917, said, big mistake.

00:15:58.154 --> 00:15:59.320
The data shows the opposite.

00:15:59.320 --> 00:16:00.610
The universe is static.

00:16:00.610 --> 00:16:03.490
The Milky Way galaxy is just
sitting here, kind of floating,

00:16:03.490 --> 00:16:06.390
and beyond it is a void,
sort of like looking

00:16:06.390 --> 00:16:07.620
to Donald Trump's mind.

00:16:07.620 --> 00:16:10.960
There's just nothing there,
maybe some malicious entities

00:16:10.960 --> 00:16:13.200
and a little bit of
sneering coming back at us.

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:14.750
That's it.

00:16:14.750 --> 00:16:16.700
So Einstein had to
put in a modification

00:16:16.700 --> 00:16:18.945
to his equation, the
famous lambda term.

00:16:18.945 --> 00:16:20.570
And instead of this
beautiful symmetry,

00:16:20.570 --> 00:16:22.819
where he thought not so much
that he detected the hand

00:16:22.819 --> 00:16:25.560
of God-- he wasn't an atheist.

00:16:25.560 --> 00:16:27.520
He wasn't a formal
religious believer.

00:16:27.520 --> 00:16:28.560
He was anti-atheist.

00:16:28.560 --> 00:16:29.620
He said, how could
you be so sure?

00:16:29.620 --> 00:16:31.630
He was sort of in-between,
kind of like Spinoza,

00:16:31.630 --> 00:16:33.160
if you interested in pantheism.

00:16:33.160 --> 00:16:34.464
It's quite extraordinary.

00:16:34.464 --> 00:16:35.880
There are subtle
structures there.

00:16:35.880 --> 00:16:37.740
He didn't know why or
what they came from.

00:16:37.740 --> 00:16:41.100
He once gave an image of humans
as being like a little boy

00:16:41.100 --> 00:16:43.070
in a big library in the dark.

00:16:43.070 --> 00:16:44.310
It's at night.

00:16:44.310 --> 00:16:45.740
It's maybe foggy out.

00:16:45.740 --> 00:16:48.080
And the walls of
the library, there's

00:16:48.080 --> 00:16:49.750
all these bookshelves
around with books.

00:16:49.750 --> 00:16:52.150
And in those books, are the
secrets of the universe.

00:16:52.150 --> 00:16:53.010
They actually exist.

00:16:53.010 --> 00:16:54.950
They've been specified
really clearly.

00:16:54.950 --> 00:16:57.630
Very occasionally, the
brightest members of our species

00:16:57.630 --> 00:17:00.320
can walk forward, go up to
one of the books, open it,

00:17:00.320 --> 00:17:01.600
and you'll actually see it.

00:17:01.600 --> 00:17:03.670
One line might say,
equals MC squared.

00:17:03.670 --> 00:17:04.430
Wow.

00:17:04.430 --> 00:17:08.442
Another might have the
tensor behind G equals T.

00:17:08.442 --> 00:17:10.900
But then we usually have to
close it, go back, and retreat.

00:17:10.900 --> 00:17:12.329
But we know it's there waiting.

00:17:12.329 --> 00:17:13.790
Einstein loved that.

00:17:13.790 --> 00:17:15.160
Newton had seen some things.

00:17:15.160 --> 00:17:17.380
Einstein was lucky enough
to see some things.

00:17:17.380 --> 00:17:18.810
Future generations could also.

00:17:18.810 --> 00:17:20.660
It's a wonderful platonic dream.

00:17:20.660 --> 00:17:23.510
Anyway, he felt bad that he had
to modify that simple G equals

00:17:23.510 --> 00:17:27.000
T, but he said, OK, if the data
doesn't show that it's correct,

00:17:27.000 --> 00:17:28.010
I'll have to modify.

00:17:28.010 --> 00:17:29.970
So he made his equation
ugly for 10 years.

00:17:29.970 --> 00:17:32.880
10 years later, Hubble in
California and other people

00:17:32.880 --> 00:17:35.270
said, oy, did we get it wrong.

00:17:35.270 --> 00:17:36.410
Oy, did we get it wrong.

00:17:36.410 --> 00:17:39.294
I'm adding the "oy" they
probably didn't say "oy."

00:17:39.294 --> 00:17:40.960
And they said the
universe is expanding.

00:17:40.960 --> 00:17:43.832
They found this wonderful
evidence that it's expanding

00:17:43.832 --> 00:17:45.790
and each part is expanding
from the other parts

00:17:45.790 --> 00:17:47.180
at a terrific rate.

00:17:47.180 --> 00:17:48.840
And Einstein was
so happy at that.

00:17:48.840 --> 00:17:49.926
He said "I knew it.

00:17:49.926 --> 00:17:50.800
I knew it all along."

00:17:50.800 --> 00:17:54.400
Have any of you, here seen
"Galaxy Quest," the film?

00:17:54.400 --> 00:17:56.450
Remember there's
this teenage boy

00:17:56.450 --> 00:17:58.030
on Earth, who
believes that aliens

00:17:58.030 --> 00:17:59.330
are speaking to him and stuff.

00:17:59.330 --> 00:18:00.580
And nobody believes
him and stuff.

00:18:00.580 --> 00:18:01.000
He says, oh, yeah.

00:18:01.000 --> 00:18:01.310
I know.

00:18:01.310 --> 00:18:02.060
It's just made up.

00:18:02.060 --> 00:18:03.779
And then he actually sees them.

00:18:03.779 --> 00:18:04.320
That's right.

00:18:04.320 --> 00:18:05.111
He said, I knew it.

00:18:05.111 --> 00:18:05.850
I knew all along.

00:18:05.850 --> 00:18:06.724
It was actually true.

00:18:06.724 --> 00:18:08.390
So that was Einstein
after 10 years.

00:18:08.390 --> 00:18:12.130
He realized he should have
stuck to his original thing.

00:18:12.130 --> 00:18:14.750
The experimental
evidence was agreed

00:18:14.750 --> 00:18:17.790
on by all the astronomers in
the world, but they were wrong.

00:18:17.790 --> 00:18:20.407
If he had just held
his nerve a bit longer,

00:18:20.407 --> 00:18:21.740
he would have been proven right.

00:18:21.740 --> 00:18:22.860
How cool is that?

00:18:22.860 --> 00:18:23.990
Two simple forms.

00:18:23.990 --> 00:18:26.030
Two simple tensors,
G equals T. Again,

00:18:26.030 --> 00:18:28.060
I'm summarizing,
but basically, that.

00:18:28.060 --> 00:18:30.600
That somebody came up with
in their head in Berlin

00:18:30.600 --> 00:18:35.220
during World War I, predicted
that our local cluster

00:18:35.220 --> 00:18:37.860
is expanding away from
other parts of the galaxy.

00:18:37.860 --> 00:18:40.190
How utterly extraordinary
that advanced

00:18:40.190 --> 00:18:42.250
primates can do
something like that.

00:18:42.250 --> 00:18:43.360
It was wonderful.

00:18:46.860 --> 00:18:49.309
So what Einstein did
here-- so he came up here.

00:18:49.309 --> 00:18:50.850
So one of his
principles, there would

00:18:50.850 --> 00:18:53.650
be say G equals T, and
the things he found there,

00:18:53.650 --> 00:18:56.620
it showed that the
universe was expanding.

00:18:56.620 --> 00:18:57.830
So I'll do like that.

00:18:57.830 --> 00:18:59.370
It shows the universe
was expanding.

00:18:59.370 --> 00:19:04.907
It also explained
how Mercury wobbled

00:19:04.907 --> 00:19:05.990
as it went around the Sun.

00:19:05.990 --> 00:19:08.090
Mercury's orbit wasn't
quite what you would think.

00:19:08.090 --> 00:19:12.135
The curve down there by the Sun,
the decay of that trampoline

00:19:12.135 --> 00:19:15.790
or rubber sheet was greater than
Newton would have predicted.

00:19:15.790 --> 00:19:17.760
Mercury I believe is that.

