And then there's even
stranger things happening.

00:28:36.580 --> 00:28:38.550
When this company,
here, was formed,

00:28:38.550 --> 00:28:41.080
hipsters and [INAUDIBLE]
didn't exist. [INAUDIBLE]

00:28:41.080 --> 00:28:42.360
was a terrible slum.

00:28:42.360 --> 00:28:43.740
Brooklyn was a
place where people

00:28:43.740 --> 00:28:46.290
went if they got divorced
and didn't have any money.

00:28:46.290 --> 00:28:48.700
So there's people with a
slightly different culture,

00:28:48.700 --> 00:28:50.710
maybe people who don't
like to own cars.

00:28:50.710 --> 00:28:52.160
It's no longer cool to own cars.

00:28:52.160 --> 00:28:53.640
It isn't part of
your definition.

00:28:53.640 --> 00:28:55.360
A better definition
could be, I don't

00:28:55.360 --> 00:28:58.000
know, having real life
experiences, live music

00:28:58.000 --> 00:28:59.730
or genuine fitness,
or triathlons.

00:28:59.730 --> 00:29:00.810
Something like that.

00:29:00.810 --> 00:29:04.960
So new categories are coming up.

00:29:04.960 --> 00:29:07.694
Very occasionally people from
here can change themselves,

00:29:07.694 --> 00:29:08.860
but it usually doesn't work.

00:29:08.860 --> 00:29:10.740
Remember, the Cavendish
lab had to jump over

00:29:10.740 --> 00:29:12.350
to a different view.

00:29:12.350 --> 00:29:15.300
They couldn't modify looking
what's inside the atom.

00:29:15.300 --> 00:29:17.700
To go in there, they had
to have new people come in.

00:29:17.700 --> 00:29:18.990
Rutherford died.

00:29:18.990 --> 00:29:20.800
Max Planck, the
great physicist, once

00:29:20.800 --> 00:29:23.930
said, "You never out argue your
opponents, you out live them."

00:29:23.930 --> 00:29:25.530
And that's something.

00:29:25.530 --> 00:29:26.440
So went over there.

00:29:26.440 --> 00:29:28.610
Occasionally, a person
can make that move across

00:29:28.610 --> 00:29:29.530
and move sideways.

00:29:29.530 --> 00:29:32.335
So think of, again to
the extent, if search

00:29:32.335 --> 00:29:33.710
is going to have
limits with some

00:29:33.710 --> 00:29:36.560
of these other things over
here, new data bits on here,

00:29:36.560 --> 00:29:38.080
suppose you have something else.

00:29:38.080 --> 00:29:38.810
Alphabet.

00:29:38.810 --> 00:29:40.050
Lots of things over here.

00:29:40.050 --> 00:29:40.790
Quite different.

00:29:40.790 --> 00:29:42.971
So there's a big structure.

00:29:42.971 --> 00:29:43.470
Like that.

00:29:43.470 --> 00:29:45.960
And then from there, you can
maybe apply to these things

00:29:45.960 --> 00:29:48.590
better, you can apply to
those, and maybe, who knows

00:29:48.590 --> 00:29:49.910
fresh things will come up.

00:29:49.910 --> 00:29:50.670
We don't know.

00:29:50.670 --> 00:29:53.950
Now the question is,
who fills those slots?

00:29:53.950 --> 00:29:55.180
Who fills those slots?

00:29:55.180 --> 00:29:57.200
Einstein went to
one slot up here

00:29:57.200 --> 00:29:58.793
and he could not move across.

00:29:58.793 --> 00:29:59.840
Neils Bohr said, come.

00:29:59.840 --> 00:30:00.340
Come on.

00:30:00.340 --> 00:30:01.370
It's different from
what you've learned.

00:30:01.370 --> 00:30:01.920
Come on.

00:30:01.920 --> 00:30:03.860
Yes, you were really great
at university doing this.

00:30:03.860 --> 00:30:05.901
Yes, you were terrific
coming up with these tools

00:30:05.901 --> 00:30:08.760
and these tensors, come over
here and use this new stuff.

00:30:08.760 --> 00:30:10.280
You'll come up
with great things.

00:30:10.280 --> 00:30:13.200
And the sadness, the pathos,
is that Einstein's mind

00:30:13.200 --> 00:30:14.370
was up to it.

00:30:14.370 --> 00:30:17.429
As an older man, he
said, one implication

00:30:17.429 --> 00:30:19.470
of this quantum mechanics,
if it were to be true,

00:30:19.470 --> 00:30:20.920
is quantum entanglement.

00:30:20.920 --> 00:30:21.990
That's almost impossible.

00:30:21.990 --> 00:30:23.700
His mathematics
was exactly right.

00:30:23.700 --> 00:30:27.452
This in 1935.

00:30:27.452 --> 00:30:29.910
A century after that, I think
we'll have quite nice quantum

00:30:29.910 --> 00:30:30.560
computers.

00:30:30.560 --> 00:30:32.197
A bit specialized,
but doing well.

00:30:32.197 --> 00:30:33.780
He came up with
gravitational lensing.

00:30:33.780 --> 00:30:35.500
All of this is as an old man.

00:30:35.500 --> 00:30:37.970
His brain was terrific, but he
just ventured there briefly,

00:30:37.970 --> 00:30:38.970
and would go right back.

00:30:38.970 --> 00:30:40.920
Oh, I've got to do
it this old way.

00:30:40.920 --> 00:30:43.040
So very rarely, can
one move across.

00:30:43.040 --> 00:30:45.540
Sometimes you have to
acquire brand new people.

00:30:45.540 --> 00:30:47.040
That's why many
companies do well.

00:30:47.040 --> 00:30:51.300
They have entire new groups,
either spun off or brought in

00:30:51.300 --> 00:30:51.990
or something.

00:30:51.990 --> 00:30:53.950
Occasionally, however,
magnificent people like,

00:30:53.950 --> 00:30:56.964
Bork can go up and work
across themselves and step,

00:30:56.964 --> 00:30:59.130
step by step into these
different things, which will

00:30:59.130 --> 00:31:00.600
have those fresh implications.

00:31:00.600 --> 00:31:03.160
So I leave you with a
question, are we Niels Bohr,

00:31:03.160 --> 00:31:04.282
or are we Albert Einstein?

00:31:04.282 --> 00:31:05.990
And after reading this
book you'll think,

00:31:05.990 --> 00:31:08.410
gosh, I used to think
Einstein was terrific,

00:31:08.410 --> 00:31:11.150
but now I don't want
to be like him at all.

00:31:11.150 --> 00:31:11.934
Thank you.

00:31:11.934 --> 00:31:17.339
[APPLAUSE]

00:31:17.339 --> 00:31:19.630
SPEAKER: Thank you very much
we have time for questions

00:31:19.630 --> 00:31:22.948
so please wait for a microphone.

00:31:28.640 --> 00:31:31.390
AUDIENCE: So Einstein created
Schrodinger's cat, didn't he?

00:31:31.390 --> 00:31:32.256
DAVID BODANIS: Yes.

00:31:32.256 --> 00:31:35.751
AUDIENCE: So that was basically
saying quantum physics is

00:31:35.751 --> 00:31:36.500
ridiculous, right?

00:31:40.579 --> 00:31:42.370
DAVID BODANIS: I don't
want to ask hands up

00:31:42.370 --> 00:31:45.110
of people who don't know
about Schrodinger's cat

00:31:45.110 --> 00:31:47.250
so I'll give a background.

00:31:47.250 --> 00:31:49.790
One conclusion, I would
say, is that if a man named

00:31:49.790 --> 00:31:51.880
Schrodinger, if you were
transformed into a cat,

00:31:51.880 --> 00:31:52.940
like you stepped
out of the internet,

00:31:52.940 --> 00:31:54.096
and, oh, I'm a cat
and stuff, and there's

00:31:54.096 --> 00:31:55.679
these strange people
around, and a man

00:31:55.679 --> 00:31:57.710
named Schrodinger comes
up to you smiling says,

00:31:57.710 --> 00:31:59.126
would you like to
go home with me?

00:31:59.126 --> 00:32:01.250
The answer is, no,
under no circumstances.

00:32:01.250 --> 00:32:02.620
It's not a good idea.

00:32:02.620 --> 00:32:04.820
Schrodinger was a man
that Einstein really loved

00:32:04.820 --> 00:32:06.830
because of his personal life.

00:32:06.830 --> 00:32:08.900
Schrodinger's wife
used to reward him

00:32:08.900 --> 00:32:10.280
when he had great results.

00:32:10.280 --> 00:32:12.580
She would introduce him
to really nice twins

00:32:12.580 --> 00:32:14.580
to go off to the
mountain with and stuff.

00:32:14.580 --> 00:32:17.940
They said about Schrodinger when
he came to Oxford in the 1930s,

00:32:17.940 --> 00:32:20.210
"To arrive at Oxford with
one wife is bad enough,

00:32:20.210 --> 00:32:22.420
to arrive with two,
really excessive."

00:32:22.420 --> 00:32:23.940
So Schrodinger
had this wild sort

00:32:23.940 --> 00:32:25.770
of bohemian life,
which Einstein liked.

00:32:25.770 --> 00:32:27.895
That's one reason Einstein
grew his hair like that.

00:32:27.895 --> 00:32:29.936
When he was young, he was
actually kind of dishy.

00:32:29.936 --> 00:32:31.030
He was a good looking guy.

00:32:31.030 --> 00:32:34.020
When he was rowing, people said,
whoa, really muscly and stuff.

00:32:34.020 --> 00:32:36.150
And he would sail
and row and stuff.

00:32:36.150 --> 00:32:38.460
But later in bourgeois
Berlin in the 1920s,

00:32:38.460 --> 00:32:40.202
he wanted to fight
that to say, you

00:32:40.202 --> 00:32:42.160
don't have to line up
and be exactly like that.

00:32:42.160 --> 00:32:44.641
His second wife was
incredibly particular.

00:32:44.641 --> 00:32:46.640
Albert, I don't think
that's quite the right way

00:32:46.640 --> 00:32:47.400
to hold our forks.

00:32:47.400 --> 00:32:48.191
That sort of thing.

00:32:48.191 --> 00:32:51.394
So we did the hair as
some sort of resistance.

00:32:51.394 --> 00:32:53.060
So he liked Schrodinger,
and the two men

00:32:53.060 --> 00:32:54.290
were really good friends.

00:32:54.290 --> 00:32:57.040
And they collaborated in
the mid-1930s by letter.

00:32:57.040 --> 00:33:00.240
Schrodinger had gotten a job
in Dublin, of all places.

00:33:00.240 --> 00:33:03.240
It turns out, the guy who ran
Ireland at the time, de Valera,

00:33:03.240 --> 00:33:04.240
had studied mathematics.

00:33:04.240 --> 00:33:06.070
So he respected Schrodinger.

00:33:06.070 --> 00:33:08.610
And in their correspondence,
they came up with this notion.

00:33:08.610 --> 00:33:10.440
It turns out very
often, people come up

00:33:10.440 --> 00:33:12.200
with a notion to
disprove a theory,

00:33:12.200 --> 00:33:14.520
and that notion is really good.

00:33:14.520 --> 00:33:16.399
And the reason is, we
don't like humiliation.

00:33:16.399 --> 00:33:17.190
We don't like fear.

00:33:17.190 --> 00:33:19.790
A friend of mine was a very
successful TV and film writer

00:33:19.790 --> 00:33:20.532
and producer.

00:33:20.532 --> 00:33:21.490
And he was really good.

00:33:21.490 --> 00:33:23.930
Then when he got a lot of money,
he sort of lost his creativity.

00:33:23.930 --> 00:33:26.100
And he tried all sorts of ways
to get his creativity back.

00:33:26.100 --> 00:33:28.260
He tried working with bright
young people, going to museums,

00:33:28.260 --> 00:33:29.426
working in different fields.

00:33:29.426 --> 00:33:30.180
None of it worked.

00:33:30.180 --> 00:33:32.150
And then his business
partner ripped him off.

00:33:32.150 --> 00:33:33.370
And boy, was he motivated.

00:33:33.370 --> 00:33:35.080
He started writing
terrific stuff.

00:33:35.080 --> 00:33:37.420
So Einstein still
disliked the fact

00:33:37.420 --> 00:33:38.800
he'd been pushed to the side.

00:33:38.800 --> 00:33:40.860
So that brought
up his creativity

00:33:40.860 --> 00:33:41.790
to a real high level.

00:33:41.790 --> 00:33:44.484
If you're fired from a
company, you want to show them.

00:33:44.484 --> 00:33:45.400
You're full of energy.

00:33:45.400 --> 00:33:46.360
You have to show them.

00:33:46.360 --> 00:33:48.170
So he came up with,
in correspondence,

00:33:48.170 --> 00:33:48.878
with Schrodinger.

00:33:48.878 --> 00:33:51.419
Schrodinger was
involved a little bit

00:33:51.419 --> 00:33:52.960
with this notion of
Heisenberg's cat,

00:33:52.960 --> 00:33:55.820
that if there's no
way, whatsoever,

00:33:55.820 --> 00:33:57.230
to predict if a
certain particles

00:33:57.230 --> 00:34:00.270
going to decay this
way or decay that way,

00:34:00.270 --> 00:34:02.020
then the following
curious effect happens.

00:34:02.020 --> 00:34:04.730
And sorry, suppose you
can't predict which way it's

00:34:04.730 --> 00:34:08.980
going to go, and will you
only know or will it only

00:34:08.980 --> 00:34:10.330
happen once you look at it?

00:34:10.330 --> 00:34:12.380
Suppose that particles
inside a box.

00:34:12.380 --> 00:34:15.159
Suppose the poor cat
is inside the box.

00:34:15.159 --> 00:34:16.929
Suppose a large gun.

00:34:16.929 --> 00:34:20.080
You see the viciousness of quiet
often vegetarian physicist.

00:34:20.080 --> 00:34:23.150
They're like, should the
gun have impaling hooks?

00:34:23.150 --> 00:34:26.040
Should there be a little
trapdoor underneath?

00:34:26.040 --> 00:34:28.513
And suppose, if the particle
decays and goes this way,

00:34:28.513 --> 00:34:29.179
nothing happens.

00:34:29.179 --> 00:34:31.000
The cat walks around.

00:34:31.000 --> 00:34:32.770
If the particle decays
and goes that way,

00:34:32.770 --> 00:34:37.300
a big gun blasts it
to smithereens, right?

00:34:37.300 --> 00:34:41.489
In a standard interpretation
of quantum mechanics,

00:34:41.489 --> 00:34:43.540
not only do you not
only know until you

00:34:43.540 --> 00:34:48.929
open the box which way
the particles decayed,

00:34:48.929 --> 00:34:50.650
it hasn't happened.

00:34:50.650 --> 00:34:53.550
It's ambiguous until
you open it and look,

00:34:53.550 --> 00:34:56.030
that the actual observation
helps create it.

00:34:56.030 --> 00:34:57.510
Einstein thought
that was insane.

00:34:57.510 --> 00:34:59.510
But yet, a lot of
evidence, again, I'm

00:34:59.510 --> 00:35:02.250
being metaphorical about it, a
lot of evidence backed it up.

00:35:02.250 --> 00:35:03.750
The question, of
course, is Einstein

00:35:03.750 --> 00:35:06.490
said, well, in that case,
is the cat alive or dead

00:35:06.490 --> 00:35:07.930
before you open the box, right?

00:35:07.930 --> 00:35:09.750
We don't know which
way the particle went

00:35:09.750 --> 00:35:11.294
and if the trigger
was pulled or not.

00:35:11.294 --> 00:35:12.460
So is the cat alive or dead?

00:35:12.460 --> 00:35:15.090
And clearly it can't be in a
superposition of two states,

00:35:15.090 --> 00:35:16.270
half dead and half alive.

00:35:16.270 --> 00:35:18.020
On the other hand, if
any of you have ever

00:35:18.020 --> 00:35:20.750
taken the northern line in
London at about 8:00 AM,

00:35:20.750 --> 00:35:22.450
you understand,
many people can be

00:35:22.450 --> 00:35:24.140
in that superposition
of two states,

00:35:24.140 --> 00:35:27.240
half dead and half alive.

00:35:27.240 --> 00:35:28.670
And they came up
with that notion

00:35:28.670 --> 00:35:30.650
to sort of disprove
quantum mechanics.

00:35:30.650 --> 00:35:33.000
And people like Niels Bohr
and other bright young people

00:35:33.000 --> 00:35:35.180
working with him
thought, good point.

00:35:35.180 --> 00:35:35.750
Good point.

00:35:35.750 --> 00:35:37.440
Yep, there's a
superposition of states

00:35:37.440 --> 00:35:38.910
until the observation
takes place

00:35:38.910 --> 00:35:40.330
and that has certain
consequences.

00:35:40.330 --> 00:35:42.180
And low and behold,
those consequences

00:35:42.180 --> 00:35:43.690
were used by John
Bardeen, who was

00:35:43.690 --> 00:35:46.840
working at Princeton at the
time, to develop transistor.

00:35:46.840 --> 00:35:48.140
It's actually true.

00:35:48.140 --> 00:35:49.520
How curious is that?

00:35:49.520 --> 00:35:52.100
Einstein wouldn't step
sideways to accept it

00:35:52.100 --> 00:35:54.150
because he had
been so comfortable

00:35:54.150 --> 00:35:56.890
in that previous position.

00:35:56.890 --> 00:35:58.629
I have a little
addendum to the answer,

00:35:58.629 --> 00:36:00.670
but I'm going to stop
giving really long answers.

00:36:00.670 --> 00:36:05.100
If there's time, Just remind me
about the playing card problem.

00:36:05.100 --> 00:36:07.718
But I'd like to have some
more questions first.

00:36:07.718 --> 00:36:09.086
SPEAKER: Who has questions?

00:36:12.724 --> 00:36:14.540
Any questions?

