arthritic, and what he loved

00:38:11.100 --> 00:38:12.600
was just noodling
away on the piano.

00:38:12.600 --> 00:38:15.410
He would noodle for hours and
hours on hours, and Berlin,

00:38:15.410 --> 00:38:16.910
and Princeton, a
little bit of jazz,

00:38:16.910 --> 00:38:20.654
a little bit of classical,
all sorts of stuff.

00:38:20.654 --> 00:38:22.070
Aesthetics meant
everything to him

00:38:22.070 --> 00:38:26.230
because he felt they were signs
of something very, very true.

00:38:26.230 --> 00:38:30.140
And it drove him into isolation.

00:38:30.140 --> 00:38:32.200
How sad is that?

00:38:32.200 --> 00:38:35.723
Next

00:38:35.723 --> 00:38:36.514
SPEAKER: Questions.

00:38:55.610 --> 00:38:56.860
DAVID BODANIS: Great question.

00:38:56.860 --> 00:39:00.140
So out of all the mistakes,
what was the worst,

00:39:00.140 --> 00:39:01.690
the most fundamental mistake.

00:39:01.690 --> 00:39:04.335
And many people think the
mistake was modifying the G

00:39:04.335 --> 00:39:05.420
equals T equation.

00:39:05.420 --> 00:39:08.110
Again, that's just a
metaphor, modifying and adding

00:39:08.110 --> 00:39:10.226
extra terms, but
that was a mistake,

00:39:10.226 --> 00:39:12.600
but it's a mistake that anybody
can make and then fix it.

00:39:12.600 --> 00:39:12.940
Oh, I see.

00:39:12.940 --> 00:39:13.580
I was wrong.

00:39:13.580 --> 00:39:15.330
And you go back with
the same attitude

00:39:15.330 --> 00:39:16.790
that he had when he was young.

00:39:16.790 --> 00:39:18.900
That you would climb up
here, which is beautiful,

00:39:18.900 --> 00:39:21.370
but then you would check things
against the consequences.

00:39:21.370 --> 00:39:23.510
And if ugly facts
really got in the way,

00:39:23.510 --> 00:39:25.510
you would have to change
this, however beautiful

00:39:25.510 --> 00:39:26.570
it was going up.

00:39:26.570 --> 00:39:28.790
So I think his mistake
wasn't the scientific mistake

00:39:28.790 --> 00:39:30.862
about the lambda,
the extra term,

00:39:30.862 --> 00:39:32.070
anybody could have done that.

00:39:32.070 --> 00:39:35.670
The mistake was
diving in and saying

00:39:35.670 --> 00:39:37.280
it was a psychological mistake.

00:39:37.280 --> 00:39:38.370
I've been burned once.

00:39:38.370 --> 00:39:40.520
I'm never going to be
burned again, right?

00:39:40.520 --> 00:39:42.950
Tony Blair had a
possibility early

00:39:42.950 --> 00:39:44.740
in his a tenure
as prime minister

00:39:44.740 --> 00:39:48.920
to help NATO forces go into
Kosovo, and a lot of people

00:39:48.920 --> 00:39:49.990
said, don't do that.

00:39:49.990 --> 00:39:50.822
It's imperialism.

00:39:50.822 --> 00:39:51.780
It's not going to work.

00:39:51.780 --> 00:39:53.113
It's really messy on the ground.

00:39:53.113 --> 00:39:54.030
He ignored them.

00:39:54.030 --> 00:39:57.450
He went into Kosovo, and on
the whole it worked quite well.

00:39:57.450 --> 00:40:00.240
A few years later he
wanted to go into Iraq.

00:40:00.240 --> 00:40:02.280
People said, don't go into Iraq.

00:40:02.280 --> 00:40:03.980
You're going to mess things up.

00:40:03.980 --> 00:40:06.420
It's a hornet's nest,
everything will get worse.

00:40:06.420 --> 00:40:09.664
And he said, they said that
before, and I was right.

00:40:09.664 --> 00:40:11.830
I stuck to my guns I'm going
to stick my guns again.

00:40:11.830 --> 00:40:13.970
And in fact, he was
wrong the second time.

00:40:13.970 --> 00:40:16.240
So that was Einstein's
problem, that second mistake.

00:40:16.240 --> 00:40:18.840
Now it happens a lot to people
who are at the top level,

00:40:18.840 --> 00:40:20.760
because they were so
successful before.

00:40:20.760 --> 00:40:23.440
If I have like a plausible
hypothesis, and then

00:40:23.440 --> 00:40:25.729
its proven wrong, and then
it's later proven right,

00:40:25.729 --> 00:40:27.770
that's nice but it's just
a plausible hypothesis,

00:40:27.770 --> 00:40:31.160
but if I come up with
general relativity, wow,

00:40:31.160 --> 00:40:35.090
and that's finally proven right
again, I'm really not cocky,

00:40:35.090 --> 00:40:38.280
but I'm very confident
in my beliefs.

00:40:38.280 --> 00:40:39.296
I'm speaking for myself.

00:40:39.296 --> 00:40:40.920
I feel I've been able
to find something

00:40:40.920 --> 00:40:42.180
true about the universe.

00:40:42.180 --> 00:40:46.290
The people who hustle really,
really hard to get to the top

00:40:46.290 --> 00:40:48.270
usually have one stick
one special approach

00:40:48.270 --> 00:40:50.190
that really, really
works, and they

00:40:50.190 --> 00:40:51.950
have to push hard to get it.

00:40:51.950 --> 00:40:53.480
And it's often a
magical approach

00:40:53.480 --> 00:40:55.450
it almost never happens twice.

00:40:55.450 --> 00:40:59.220
Lester Thurow, the guy at MIT,
who cruelly has been described

00:40:59.220 --> 00:41:01.880
as less than thorough,
which is mean,

00:41:01.880 --> 00:41:04.420
pointed out that hardly
anybody who creates a company,

00:41:04.420 --> 00:41:06.760
creates two different
companies, ever.

00:41:06.760 --> 00:41:08.450
Occasionally there's
people who do it.

00:41:08.450 --> 00:41:11.870
That idea, unfortunately,
came to me as a teenager.

00:41:11.870 --> 00:41:14.140
I read his book,
and it bothered me

00:41:14.140 --> 00:41:17.130
so much that the first time I
had a bestseller, I thought,

00:41:17.130 --> 00:41:18.860
yeah, well.

00:41:18.860 --> 00:41:20.900
But I had a second
one, 10 years later.

00:41:20.900 --> 00:41:22.070
I said, yes, Lester.

00:41:22.070 --> 00:41:23.200
Yes, we can do it.

00:41:23.200 --> 00:41:24.339
We can do a separate thing.

00:41:24.339 --> 00:41:25.380
First time could be luck.

00:41:25.380 --> 00:41:28.526
Second time OK, one knows
how to do this stuff.

00:41:28.526 --> 00:41:30.002
AUDIENCE: SoI have a question.

00:41:40.930 --> 00:41:43.790
DAVID BODANIS: I'm amazed at
what human beings could do,

00:41:43.790 --> 00:41:47.430
and also ordinary human beings.

00:41:47.430 --> 00:41:50.300
I grew up in an ordinary
Jewish family in Chicago

00:41:50.300 --> 00:41:52.810
after World War II, and many
people in the neighborhood

00:41:52.810 --> 00:41:55.030
would have a picture of
Einstein up on refrigerator

00:41:55.030 --> 00:41:58.080
or an encyclopedia about
this thing of Einstein,

00:41:58.080 --> 00:42:00.520
and I thought this is
a noble and good man.

00:42:00.520 --> 00:42:03.980
I feel some connection with him,
but I had no idea what he did.

00:42:03.980 --> 00:42:05.234
I had no idea.

00:42:05.234 --> 00:42:07.400
Some people, I don't know
if they invent a computer,

00:42:07.400 --> 00:42:09.910
or they invent a car,
or a particular device,

00:42:09.910 --> 00:42:11.676
or an airplane, it's beautiful.

00:42:11.676 --> 00:42:13.300
But when I was a
little child, I didn't

00:42:13.300 --> 00:42:14.466
know what Einstein had done.

00:42:14.466 --> 00:42:17.440
At university I learned
about it and I was amazed.

00:42:17.440 --> 00:42:19.880
It was sort of like listening
to Mozart for the first time

00:42:19.880 --> 00:42:23.320
or in my case Mozart especially
the "Clarinet Concerto,"

00:42:23.320 --> 00:42:25.180
but like a good
blues or something.

00:42:25.180 --> 00:42:27.985
You listen to it and feels
this is really true, sort of

00:42:27.985 --> 00:42:29.110
like on a really good date.

00:42:29.110 --> 00:42:31.400
On a mediocre date, you
tell your cute stories.

00:42:31.400 --> 00:42:33.700
They tell their cute stories,
but on a really good day

00:42:33.700 --> 00:42:34.750
you're just connected.

00:42:34.750 --> 00:42:36.260
You're just directly connected.

00:42:36.260 --> 00:42:38.200
There's no artifice from
top to bottom stuff.

00:42:38.200 --> 00:42:39.360
So when I was learning
about Einstein,

00:42:39.360 --> 00:42:41.170
I thought, wow, he cuts
through in the universe.

00:42:41.170 --> 00:42:42.294
He saw what's really there.

00:42:42.294 --> 00:42:46.940
This notion of geometry
inducing the sensation of force

00:42:46.940 --> 00:42:48.570
as with people going
to the North Pole

00:42:48.570 --> 00:42:50.830
and feeling it pull together
or the gravity coming

00:42:50.830 --> 00:42:52.070
that way, that's incredible.

00:42:52.070 --> 00:42:53.820
So I really wanted to
share it, and then I

00:42:53.820 --> 00:42:55.970
wanted to find out
how did he do it.

00:42:55.970 --> 00:42:57.410
I mean what, sort of man was he?

00:42:57.410 --> 00:42:58.680
What was his background?

00:42:58.680 --> 00:43:01.140
One thing that helps in
a background like that,

00:43:01.140 --> 00:43:03.954
is to be not a total outsider,
if you're a total outsider,

00:43:03.954 --> 00:43:05.620
you don't have enough
education, but not

00:43:05.620 --> 00:43:07.280
to be a total insider either.

00:43:07.280 --> 00:43:09.060
It helps to be sort
of on the edge.

00:43:09.060 --> 00:43:12.150
Moderate discrimination works
really, really well in science

00:43:12.150 --> 00:43:13.520
and in business very much.

00:43:13.520 --> 00:43:15.716
Total discrimination, they
don't give you a chance.

00:43:15.716 --> 00:43:17.590
Moderate discrimination,
you know two things.

00:43:17.590 --> 00:43:19.220
A You have to work
a little bit harder

00:43:19.220 --> 00:43:22.270
and B what you learned
before about the system

00:43:22.270 --> 00:43:23.590
isn't necessarily true.

00:43:23.590 --> 00:43:27.070
Suppose somebody grows up
say an extremely religious,

00:43:27.070 --> 00:43:29.260
fundamentalist, religious view.

00:43:29.260 --> 00:43:31.480
As a kid, they're taught
to say that the world is

00:43:31.480 --> 00:43:33.850
based on turtles and it's
turtles all the way down.

00:43:33.850 --> 00:43:35.730
They go to university,
and the people there

00:43:35.730 --> 00:43:37.867
who teach astronomy
say, that's nonsense.

00:43:37.867 --> 00:43:38.950
It's not like that at all.

00:43:38.950 --> 00:43:41.190
Here, I'm going to teach
you the latest results.

00:43:41.190 --> 00:43:42.800
This is what we know
is totally true.

00:43:42.800 --> 00:43:45.480
The person might think,
maybe, but maybe not.

00:43:45.480 --> 00:43:47.450
What my mother
taught me was wrong.

00:43:47.450 --> 00:43:49.570
Maybe what I learned
from you, may be that,

00:43:49.570 --> 00:43:51.571
not necessarily as wrong
as that previous thing,

00:43:51.571 --> 00:43:52.945
but I'll be a
little bit cynical.

00:43:52.945 --> 00:43:55.372
Compare that to somebody who
was, say a professor's kid,

00:43:55.372 --> 00:43:57.080
they grew up learning
the latest results,

00:43:57.080 --> 00:43:58.380
in a simplified version.

00:43:58.380 --> 00:44:01.260
These nice books you buy for
your kids when you feel guilty

00:44:01.260 --> 00:44:04.662
and you're watching Jack
Bauer save the day again.

00:44:04.662 --> 00:44:06.120
And then when they
go to university

00:44:06.120 --> 00:44:07.300
and it's more of the same.

00:44:07.300 --> 00:44:10.100
They have no reason to be
really, really critical.

00:44:10.100 --> 00:44:11.690
So Einstein was
enough of an outsider

00:44:11.690 --> 00:44:16.480
to be critical, but not so
much that he had no training.

00:44:19.462 --> 00:44:21.450
SPEAKER: Time for
more questions.

00:44:34.900 --> 00:44:39.270
DAVID BODANIS: Yeah, so how did
he hold onto his skepticism?

00:44:39.270 --> 00:44:42.690
I suppose he held up to it,
well a couple of reasons.

00:44:42.690 --> 00:44:45.740
One, he had seen that large
groups of people can be wrong.

00:44:45.740 --> 00:44:48.310
All the astronomers in
the world, everybody

00:44:48.310 --> 00:44:52.320
whether they were very
theoretical or very practical.

00:44:52.320 --> 00:44:54.140
they all were persuaded
that the universe

00:44:54.140 --> 00:44:57.220
was static for 10 years
or eight years and stuff.

00:44:57.220 --> 00:44:58.750
And it's like,
they've been wrong.

00:44:58.750 --> 00:44:59.520
They've been wrong once.

00:44:59.520 --> 00:45:01.200
What if they've been
wrong for 20 or 30 years?

00:45:01.200 --> 00:45:02.410
There were certain results.

00:45:02.410 --> 00:45:04.560
The ability to measure
things in the universe

00:45:04.560 --> 00:45:07.960
was very difficult. To measure
absolute distances is hard.

00:45:07.960 --> 00:45:11.150
We know that if we know the
absolute brightness of a car

00:45:11.150 --> 00:45:14.940
headlight at a certain distance
what we perceive of it,

00:45:14.940 --> 00:45:18.570
it is going to be high or
low, and then the intensity,

00:45:18.570 --> 00:45:21.030
and then we can work out
from an absolute magnitude

00:45:21.030 --> 00:45:22.130
how far away it is.

00:45:22.130 --> 00:45:24.420
So it took a long time
until astronomers,

00:45:24.420 --> 00:45:28.670
a woman named Henrietta
Leavitt in Boston,

00:45:28.670 --> 00:45:30.830
who managed to find
a way of measuring

00:45:30.830 --> 00:45:33.690
the distance to nearest
galaxies and that

00:45:33.690 --> 00:45:37.160
allowed us to get a proper
yardstick for the universe.

00:45:37.160 --> 00:45:38.930
So suppose Henrietta
Leavitt hadn't done

00:45:38.930 --> 00:45:41.620
that, 50 years may have passed.

00:45:41.620 --> 00:45:42.790
Einstein knew he was lucky.

00:45:42.790 --> 00:45:43.970
It only was 10 years.

00:45:43.970 --> 00:45:47.075
So it could have been past his
death, past his whole lifetime

00:45:47.075 --> 00:45:49.200
that people thought the
universe was static and low

00:45:49.200 --> 00:45:50.410
and behold it was not static.

00:45:50.410 --> 00:45:51.743
You know the greatest authority.

00:45:51.743 --> 00:45:52.490
So that was one.

00:45:52.490 --> 00:45:54.990
The other thing is,
in the 1920s and '30s

00:45:54.990 --> 00:45:57.000
he saw entire countries go mad.

00:45:57.000 --> 00:45:59.990
As countries go mad and nuts.

00:45:59.990 --> 00:46:03.700
In 1933, many books were
burned in Germany in public,

00:46:03.700 --> 00:46:07.107
including in the greatest
university town everywhere,

00:46:07.107 --> 00:46:08.690
in the world, then
it was [INAUDIBLE].

00:46:08.690 --> 00:46:12.390
It'd be like, could you imagine
if at Cambridge and, MIT and,

00:46:12.390 --> 00:46:15.705
all those places, they start
burning books with enthusiasm

00:46:15.705 --> 00:46:17.330
from the students,
and Einstein's books

00:46:17.330 --> 00:46:19.163
for some of those that
was there were burnt.

00:46:19.163 --> 00:46:20.560
It was non-Aryan physics.

00:46:20.560 --> 00:46:21.420
It was terrible.

00:46:21.420 --> 00:46:24.390
So he knew, hey, entire
organizations can go nuts.

00:46:24.390 --> 00:46:27.670
I just have to be
quiet and wait it out.

00:46:27.670 --> 00:46:28.470
But he was wrong.

